  <section>
    <h2>Methodological limits</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Generational non-uniformity:</strong> The comparison of first-generation (foreign-born), second-generation (parents foreign-born), and native-born students is not applied consistently across countries. First- and second-generation students show very different performance patterns.</li>
      <li><strong>Measurement error in socioeconomic index:</strong> PISA's ESCS index (Economic, Social and Cultural Status) is a proxy measure and does not fully capture household environments.</li>
      <li><strong>Different migrant selection profiles:</strong> Countries prioritising skilled immigration (Australia, Canada) and those receiving predominantly refugees and family reunification migrants (Nordic countries) have fundamentally different population compositions.</li>
      <li><strong>Language acquisition time:</strong> Length of residence and years of schooling in the host-country language affect performance; this is not uniformly controlled in cross-country comparisons.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What this data does not show</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Having an immigrant background does not cause lower educational performance. 83% of the gap is explained by socioeconomic circumstances (household income, parental education, cultural capital).</li>
      <li>The larger adjusted residual gaps in Nordic countries may suggest integration policy issues, but causal relationships cannot be derived directly from the statistics.</li>
      <li>Cross-country differences reflect the origin, education levels, and selection processes of migrants, not a general characteristic of "immigrant children" as a category.</li>
      <li>PISA scores measure attainment at age 15. They do not predict long-term educational outcomes or social integration results.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

